{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.29,0.03,0.07,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6676"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38259"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3806"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43466"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe headache, nausea, and vomiting. He has a medical history of non-small cell lung cancer and is currently undergoing active treatment with chemo-radiotherapy. He takes regular paracetamol and ondansetron as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits, with normal power, sensation, and reflexes in all limbs. Cranial nerve examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal numerous intracerebral metastatic lesions on CT brain with no evidence of midline shift.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous mannitol","Palliative care referral","Whole-brain radiotherapy","Neurosurgical referral","Intravenous dexamethasone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of an 82-year-old man with known non-small cell lung cancer presenting with symptoms suggestive of raised intracranial pressure and multiple brain metastases on imaging, the most appropriate next step in management is to commence \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E. Corticosteroids, particularly dexamethasone, are the first-line treatment for symptomatic brain metastases. They help reduce cerebral oedema associated with brain metastases, thereby alleviating symptoms such as headache, nausea, and vomiting. Given this patients ongoing vomiting, intravenous administration is preferred until they can tolerate oral administration. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurosurgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step in this scenario. While neurosurgical input may be valuable, the absence of midline shift and the presence of multiple metastases make immediate surgical intervention less likely to be beneficial. Neurosurgical consultation might be considered later in the management plan, particularly if there\u0027s a dominant, surgically accessible lesion causing significant mass effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used in acute settings of severely raised intracranial pressure, such as in traumatic brain injury or acute stroke with significant oedema. It\u0027s not the first-line treatment for cerebral oedema associated with brain metastases, where corticosteroids are more effective and have a more sustained effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhole-brain radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important treatment modality for multiple brain metastases and would likely be considered in this patient\u0027s management plan. However, it\u0027s not the most immediate next step. Radiotherapy planning takes time, and the patient\u0027s symptoms need to be addressed more urgently with corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalliative care referral\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in the overall management of this patient with advanced cancer and brain metastases. However, it\u0027s not the most urgent next step in addressing the patient\u0027s acute symptoms. Palliative care involvement should be integrated into the patient\u0027s care plan, but after initial symptom management with corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of brain metastases requires a multidisciplinary approach involving oncology, radiation oncology, neurosurgery, and palliative care. The immediate goal is to control symptoms and reduce cerebral oedema with corticosteroids, followed by consideration of definitive treatments such as whole-brain radiotherapy or stereotactic radiosurgery, depending on the number and location of metastases, the patient\u0027s overall condition, and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dexamethasone is the first-line treatment for symptomatic brain metastases to reduce cerebral oedema and alleviate symptoms.","CT brain is the initial imaging modality of choice for suspected brain metastases in cancer patients presenting with neurological symptoms.","Patients with multiple brain metastases often benefit from whole-brain radiotherapy to control symptoms and improve quality of life."],"references":["Mitchell DK, Kwon HJ, Kubica PA, Huff WX, O\u0027Regan R, Dey M. Brain metastases: An update on the multi-disciplinary approach of clinical management. Neurochirurgie. 2022;68(1):69-85. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33864773/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38259"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38259"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T10:34:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:36:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6676"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"update